<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 93 / Pit cuts stoke closure fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE and MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Coal has told unions it expects to cut staffing at Ellington
colliery, Northumberland, its last remaining pit in north-east England by
more than half. The move came as Mr Neil Clarke, the corporation's chairman,
indicated there was a need for further mine closures.
Mr Clarke said plans by generators to run down stocks increased pressure on
the need to cut production. His remarks fuelled expectations that the
corporation will announce further closures in the new year on top of the
seven announced in the past two months.
At Ellington unions were told to expect the loss of 650 jobs by 1996, with
180 going by April. The pit employs 1,240. Production in 1994-95 will be cut
from 2.2m tonnes to 1.5m, probably requiring a further 100 redundancies.
Further job losses are likely in 1995-96, cutting staffing to 590.
Meanwhile, British Coal is to offer cut-price coal to generators at
considerably less than production costs. It believes there will be no sales
this financial year but hopes electricity generators will buy several
million tonnes next year.
Even if it achieved that target, it is unlikely that more than 15 of the
remaining 22 pits would remain open by privatisation.
Private View, Weekend FT Page XXII
