<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 93 / Government rejects milk market shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday put at risk plans to open up the milk market in
England and Wales to competition by next April by throwing out proposals by
the Milk Marketing Board to turn itself into Milk Marque, a farmers'
voluntary co-operative.
Farmers fear the widespread criticisms of the board's reorganisation plans
voiced yesterday by the government will delay the timetable for freeing up
the market.
The government is being forced by Brussels to abolish the milk board, which
acts as an intermediary in the market by buying up all milk from farmers and
selling it on to dairies. But the board's plans to transform itself into a
co-operative have fallen foul of the European Commission's competition
authorities.
The commission indicated earlier this week that it was not happy with plans
to transfer the bulk of the board's assets directly to the proposed Milk
Marque, saying this needed further investigation.
The reorganisation plans represent the greatest shake-up in the milk
business since the board was created 60 years ago.
Mr Richard Packer, permanent secretary at the Ministry of Agriculture,
yesterday told the board that it should hold talks with dairy companies that
have condemned the reorganisation scheme. He also asked the board to look
again at its proposals for an auction system as a way of rationing milk
supplies to the highest bidder.
In addition, Mr Packer queried the transfer of certain assets such as
National Milk Records, the milk testing laboratories, and Genus, the
breeding advisory service to the new co-operative, and called into question
proposals for transferring all haulage contracts to the new body and
restrictive proposals on how often producers who sign up with Milk Marque
are allowed to leave the organisation.
Mr Andrew Dare, set to become Milk Marque's chief executive, has promised
farmers higher milk prices if they join him in April - saying that prices
will rise because the UK does not produce enough milk for its own needs. His
plans to sign up 80 per cent of producers would still give him great power
in the market.
The Dairy Trade Federation, which represents wholesale milk purchasers, has
criticised the proposed Milk Marque stranglehold on the market.
'The whole principle of reform in the milk market was to create an
environment of free competition and the board's scheme would have severely
limited it,' said Mr Neil Davidson, group executive of Northern Foods, which
plans to buy its milk directly from farmers.
</TEXT>
<XX>
