<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 93 / Sacked printers lose test case
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Sacked workers at JW Arrowsmith, the Bristol printing company which has been
picketed for nearly eight months, have had their claim for unfair dismissal
rejected by an industrial tribunal.
About 120 staff - the majority of the workforce - were dismissed in April in
a dispute over pay and conditions.
Three of the printers, supported by their union the GPMU, brought what was
regarded as a test case to the tribunal. After a nine-day hearing the
tribunal ruled it did not have jurisdiction because the three had been
offered their jobs back.
Arrowsmith had offered to re-employ the workers at their previous pay, but
said it would no longer recognise the union. It had said it could not afford
to meet the demand for a Pounds 6.50 a week pay rise and the workers were
dismissed after taking industrial action.
Mr John Price, GPMU branch officer, said yesterday that the picketing would
continue while the situation was reassessed.
'Obviously we are disappointed we have lost the first round,' he said. 'We
will be taking legal advice and the general secretary will decide how to
progress the dispute. Even at this late stage, we want a negotiated
settlement.'
</TEXT>
