<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 93 / EU Summit: Let's have a chat over dinner - Summit Diary / FT
writers report on the first day of the European Union leaders' meeting in
Brussels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL and DAVID MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The last visit of a Russian leader to Belgium was in the 18th century, so it
is said, when Peter the Great passed through. Following Boris the Great's
visit earlier this week, Belgian diplomats are hoping it won't be another
250 years before the next visit. They are particularly worried that an
incident at dinner on Thursday night might have put the chill back into
rapidly warming relations between Russia and western Europe.
'Another Berlin Wall has fallen,' Mr Yeltsin said after the EU and Russia
signed a political declaration. But over dinner on Thursday night, the
Russian leader made it clear he thought the thaw in the cold war had not
gone far enough. He petulantly pointed out that Nato's friendly intentions
seemed to stop at the Urals.
Moreover, he went on to cite its apparent chilliness towards Russia as just
the most obvious example of western Europe's deeper reluctance to snuggle up
to Russia - lack of concrete funding pledges being another example.
It took a few calming words from President Francois Mitterrand of France to
prevent the outburst becoming a full-scale diplomatic incident, officials
said yesterday. Next time around, maybe they'll soothe Mr Yeltsin's nerves
with the comprehensive trade pact he really wanted, rather than the
high-sounding promises of a declaration on greater economic and political
co-operation.
* * * *
At least hangers-on at the ministerial meetings have the sun-seeking,
island-hopping, ouzo-drinking Greek presidency of the European Union to look
forward to. It begins on January 1 and after the drizzly Belgian presidency
should be a welcome New Year tonic. Mr Theodoros Pangalos, the Greek foreign
minister, did his bit to raise summit-goers' spirits yesterday by making the
case for at least three special Greek weekend breaks on top of the scheduled
summit of EU leaders in Corfu next June. Book early to avoid disappointment.
* * * *
More demonstrations to mark yesterday's meeting, and an additional traffic
headache for Brussels police. At one point, police were predicting the
chaotic near-coincidence in Brussels of 25,000 Belgian socialist union
members, protesting against their government's austerity plans, 800 striking
teachers, 300 torch-carrying European miners, 400 young Euro-federalists,
and thousands of funereal firefighters mourning the death of a colleague.
Nothing colourful enough, however, to satisfy Sir John Kerr, Britain's top
EU diplomat, who lamented that Brussels demos were always characterised by
'too many farmers and not enough French film stars'.
* * * *
After the Lord Mayor's Show comes the muck-cart: ministers, diplomats and
journalists are bracing themselves for a nightmare on Monday when the
Belgian presidency has committed itself to hold five simultaneous
ministerial meetings in the overcrowded Charlemagne building in Brussels,
many of them charged with clearing up issues unresolved by EU leaders.
</TEXT>
