<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 93 / International Company News: Hughes Aircraft to build Dollars
660m satellite system
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Hughes Aircraft, the General Motors aerospace subsidiary which is the
world's largest owner and operator of satellites, is to build a Dollars 660m
satellite system to provide specialised telecommunications services in the
US market.
The company said it has applied to the Federal Communications Commission for
permission to launch and operate two satellites in 1998.
The satellites will service a system called Spaceway, which will provide
residential and business subscribers with specialised services such as
two-way video telephones and interactive computer transmissions.
Although Spaceway is intended to supplement terrestrial telecommunication,
Hughes said it could eventually compete directly with ground-based telephone
line and cable systems.
Mr Steven Dorfman, senior vice-president of Hughes' space and
telecommunications division, said Spaceway would send its signal to
subscribers via satellite dishes that will be smaller and cheaper than
existing dishes. Hardware that now costs between Dollars 5,000 and Dollars
10,000, could cost as little as Dollars 1,000 with Spaceway.
</TEXT>
