<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 93 / International Company News: Metallgesellschaft to reduce
foreign holdings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER, NIKKI TAIT and BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT, SYDNEY, TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Metallgesellschaft, the loss-making Frankfurt-based mining, metals and
industrial conglomerate is to reduce two of its biggest foreign
shareholdings. The sales follow agreement between the group and its bankers
this week over new lines of credit to avert a liquidity crisis.
Metallgesellschaft has sold the bulk of its indirectly-owned 14 per cent
stake in the Brisbane-based MIM Holdings for ADollars 250m (USDollars
168.9m). It also intends to sell 11.6m directly-owned shares in Metall
Mining Corporation, a Canadian mining group, for CDollars 124.7m (USDollars
94.5m), reducing its holding to 50.1 per cent.
Separately, Metallgesellschaft and Deutsche Bank denied a report that Mr
Heinz Schimmelbusch, Metallgesellschaft's chief executive, had come under
the surveillance of a specially-created committee of senior German managers.
This was alleged to be have been formed last month at the initiative of Mr
Ronaldo Schmitz, the Deutsche Bank director and chairman of the
Metallgesellschaft supervisory board, but Deutsche said the report was
groundless.
The Frankfurt group said the sales of the shareholdings were unconnected
with its current liquidity situation, and had been planned before it went
into negotiations last Friday with Deutsche Bank and Dresdner Bank.
News of the talks earlier this week prompted a 12 per cent fall in
Metallgesellschaft's share price on Monday. However, the stock has recovered
much of the original losses following the group's insistence - backed by its
bankers - that its liquidity problems are temporary. It blames them on
technical aspects of futures contracts taken out to hedge its oil delivery
business in the US.
Although proceeds of the sale of the 11.6m shares in Metall Mining Corp will
flow directly to the German parent company, the money raised in Australia on
Wednesday via the sale of 100m shares in MIM Holdings will remain with
Metall Mining, through which Metallgesellschaft owns the stake. However, the
immediate proceeds are to be invested in the development of the Canadian
company's copper activities, Mr Klaus Zeitler, the Canadian company's chief
executive said yesterday.
Analysts said the sale of the Australian company's shares could give rise to
a book profit in Metallgesellschaft's current-year accounts, and that the
German company could benefit from an increased dividend from its Canadian
subsidiary.
The 100m shares in the Australian company were sold to institutions by two
firms of stockbrokers at ADollars 2.35 each.
Bernard Simon in Toronto adds: Metallgesellschaft yesterday raised almost
CDollars 70m by selling 6.4m shares in Vancouver-based Methanex, which is
one of the world's biggest methanol producers, to Nova, the Canadian
petrochemicals and pipeline group. Metallgesellschaft was Methanex's
second-biggest shareholder with a stake of 13 per cent.
</TEXT>
