<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 93 / International Company News: Swiss telecoms group sacks chief
executive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ZURICH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Ascom, the troubled Swiss telecommunications equipment maker, yesterday
sacked its chief executive, Mr Leonardo Vannotti, and announced another
restructuring.
Ascom was formed in 1987 when three suppliers to the Swiss PTT merged. It
has struggled to develop a strategy to cope with liberalised markets.
Mr Vannotti became chief executive in 1991. He had previously held senior
positions with ABB-Asea Brown Boveri and Mr Stephan Schmidheiny's Unotec
group.
In April, Ascom shocked investors by announcing it would post a 1992 net
loss of SFr46m (Dollars 31.4m) and pass its dividend. Days earlier, it had
forecast a profit of around SFr25m.
Mr Vannotti took full responsibility, but rashly predicted a return to
profit this year. In August the group reported a loss of SFr79m in the first
half and admitted it would face a 'marked loss' in the full year.
Directors said Mr Fred Sutter, deputy chief executive, would succeed Mr
Vannotti, and they have formed a committee to direct the group during its
restructuring phase.
</TEXT>
