<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 93 / UK Company News: Compass lifted by acquisitions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Compass Group, the healthcare and catering group, yesterday announced a
sharp rise in both profits and turnover for the year to September 26 on the
back of recent acquisitions.
Pre-tax profits rose by 31 per cent to Pounds 41.5m, compared with Pounds
31.8m.
Turnover was ahead 44 per cent at Pounds 497m, including a contribution of
Pounds 156.2m from acquisitions, mainly reflecting the purchase in July of
SAS Service Partner's airport catering business via a rights issue, and last
November's acquisitions of Travellers Fare, the station caterers, and
Letheby &amp; Christopher, the sports and events caterer.
Turnover from continuing operations fell from Pounds 345.1m to Pounds
340.8m. The group attributed the decline to continued 'demanning' in the UK
because of recession.
Operating profit from continuing operations rose from Pounds 36.9m to Pounds
39.4m. A contribution of Pounds 7.4m from acquisitions took total operating
profit to Pounds 46.8m.
Mr Francis Mackay, chief executive, said the full benefits of the
acquisitions had yet to be seen as purchasing and other affinities were
sorted out over the next year or so. 'All the acquisitions have performed
well. There are no skeletons or black holes and we have not lost a single
contract in all the business we have brought on board.'
Last December Compass reorganised its catering activities into seven
divisions which target core markets from schools to boardrooms. The New
Famous Foods division, which has agreements with Burger King and Pizza Hut,
is designed to offer clients branded catering outlets.
Earlier this month Compass paid Pounds 900,000 for the 11 catering contracts
managed by the Roux brothers. Mr Mackay described the deal as the 'final
piece of the jigsaw' in the group's new strategy.
'We have created a unique catering company with enormous potential in all
market sectors. We are capable of expanding the business and we have the
wherewithal to do it,' he said yesterday.
UK catering profits were up from Pounds 24.5m to Pounds 30.6m, overseas
catering profits from Pounds 100,000 to Pounds 3.1m, and healthcare profits
from Pounds 12.3m to Pounds 13.1m.
Interest payable edged ahead from Pounds 5.1m to Pounds 5.3m. Adjusted
earnings per share rose from 33.1p to 35.9p; a final dividend of 8.56p is
proposed, giving a total for the year of 13p (12.3p).
COMMENT
These results were very much in line with expectations. Next year will
depend on how well the group digests its acquisitions, and on the rate the
contract catering market expands in the UK. The group has a toehold in
Europe through the airport catering business and the City will be watching
to see how well it tackles expanding its business outside the UK. Growth in
the healthcare sector is likely to be slow for the next couple of years.
Profits of Pounds 53m next year give a prospective multiple of 14.8, making
the stock an undemanding hold.
</TEXT>
