<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 93 / UK Company News: British Steel cannot confirm sale of plants
to Vallourec
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH STEEL reacted last night to speculation about the future of its
seamless tube business by saying it could not confirm that there was any
intention to sell its two Lanarkshire plants to Vallourec of France, writes
Andrew Baxter.
The steelmaker was responding to reports that it was in talks to sell the
Clydesdale and Imperial plants, which employ about 400 people, to the French
steel tubes producer.
There has been speculation for some time over British Steel's intentions in
the seamless tube business, which according to some estimates suffers from
excess production capacity of as much as 50 per cent worldwide.
It is understood that British Steel has had talks with Vallourec, but that
it has also been in contact with other seamless tube producers.
British Steel shut its outdated, high-cost rotary forge - used for making
the tubes - at Clydesdale two years ago, and now imports 'green' or
unfinished tubes from Vallourec and other suppliers.
It retains heat treatment equipment at Clydesdale, while the Imperial plant
finishes and threads the pipes, and also produces a sophisticated internal
coupling for the tubes under licence from Vallourec.
The tubes are used principally for 'downhole' and other applications in the
North Sea.
</TEXT>
