FT  10 DEC 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
These days Friday nights seem better on radio than television. Radio 3
starts the evening with a live relay from London's Festival Hall of a
concert by the BBC Symphony Orchestra under Andrew Davies. He conducts
Elgar's Introduction and Allegro, Vaughan Williams' Fantasia On Christmas
Carols, and Holst's Planets Suite (7.30).
That is followed by The Rebirth Of Nationalism presented by Robert Wistrich:
'The half baked theories of chauvinist intellectuals have percolated to the
lowest depths of Russian society where they have been eagerly adopted by
neo-Nazi groups ..' (9.30).
At the same moment Radio 5 begins a series called Teen Lurve which is
precisely the sort of material being mourned now that this network has been
selected to commit hara kiri in favour of a 24-hour news channel. Where else
on radio would you find a series of teen-romance dramas?
In today's opener Julie's retro punk boy friend, who plays guitar in a
thrash band, fails to gain approval from her parents.
