<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 93 / Councils fear extra demands
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
District and metropolitan councils, which will have to police the new
shopping regulations, yesterday reacted with concern to the decision by MPs.
The Labour-controlled Association of Metropolitan Authorities welcomed the
decision to put Sunday trading on a 'more clearly defined legal basis', but
said councils would have to meet extra demands.
The cost of the partial de-regulation option has been estimated by the
Institute of Public Finance at between Pounds 3m and Pounds 4m - but the
extent of the impact will differ from authority to authority.
The Local Government Management Board said that trading standards
departments would need extra funds to police the new regulations. But the
government would not meet the cost, it added.
Extra income from car parks and parking meters would have to be balanced
against extra costs from increased pressure on street cleaning, trading
standards and parking.
</TEXT>
