<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 93 / Defeated MPs lick their wounds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Opponents of Sunday shopping were nursing their bruises yesterday and
dreaming of reversing in the Lords Wednesday's defeat or during the
line-by-line committee stage.
'To tell the truth, we are all feeling a bit gutted this morning,' said one
of the key organisers of the Keep Sunday Special Campaign.
Mr Ray Powell, the Labour whip who ran the Commons end of the campaign, met
retail and church supporters yesterday to discuss resistance to the
successful six-hours option.
Keep Sunday Special is unlikely to make a final decision about tactics until
after a meeting next week, but it appears to have two options, neither of
them promising.
The first would be a guerrilla campaign during the bill's committee and
report stages.
The aim would be to toughen protection for workers who are unwilling to work
on Sundays, and possibly to reduce the permitted opening time for big shops
from six hours to four.
But amending the bill may be difficult because the government will not allow
a free vote on employment issues.
In addition the campaign's retail supporters now accept that they will have
to open on Sundays to protect market share. They may be unwilling to support
employment-protection measures which would increase their costs.
The second option would be an attempt to reinstate the Keep Sunday Special
option in the Lords. The Lords have the right to amend the bill, but are
highly unlikely to do so as it was a government manifesto commitment, and
both the principle and the six-hours option were approved by big majorities
in the Commons.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
