<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 93 / Sunday bill creates size anomaly
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Wednesday night's vote in the Commons for partial de-regulation of Sunday
trading sweeps away the restrictions of the 1950 Shops Act and will allow
all shops in England and Wales to open legally for at least six hours on
Sundays.
But if the Sunday trading bill becomes law next year it will leave one
important anomaly. A store of slightly less than 280 sq m (about 3,000 sq
ft) would be allowed to open freely, while one just above - whose range of
goods may be no bigger - would be restricted to six hours.
All shops larger than 280 sq m will be allowed to open for a continuous
period of up to six hours between 10am and 6pm. They must, however, observe
certain rules, including notifying their local authority 14 days before they
plan to open, and displaying their permitted opening times.
There are maximum fines of Pounds 5,000 for failing to notify the authority
and for trading longer than six hours, and of Pounds 500 for failing to
display the opening hours.
Some categories of shops, such as pubs, petrol stations, and restaurants are
not restricted to six hours but can open at any time.
Shops in Scotland, where Sunday trading is fully de-regulated, will continue
to enjoy the right to open at any time.
The winning option, put forward by the Shopping Hours Reform Council, avoids
many of the complications that would have arisen from the strict regulation
option put forward by Retailers for Shops Act Reform and the Keep Sunday
Special Campaign.
Opponents of wider Sunday opening have claimed that the partial
de-regulation option is in fact a thinly disguised version of total
de-regulation. Retail experts, however, say the six-hour restriction will
limit the opening of larger stores by making it unprofitable for many of
them to do so.
</TEXT>
<XX>
