<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 93 / MPs deplore Pounds 20m waste of NHS cash
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Grave concern over the waste of at least Pounds 20m on computer projects in
Wessex Regional Health Authority was expressed by the Commons public
accounts committee yesterday.
Its report refers to evidence of conflict of interest, concealment of vital
information, and 'grave shortcomings in management and financial control and
accountability'.
The Wessex authority, the National Health Service management executive and
individuals including Mr John Hoare, the authority's former general manager,
and Sir Robin Buchanan, until recently its chairman, are all criticised.
By the time the region's ambitious computerisation plans were abandoned in
1990, says the committee, at least Pounds 43m had been spent 'with little
return' and the authority accepted that Pounds 20m or more had been wasted.
The report refers to a 'near obsessional belief' in the
information-technology plans.
Much of the blame is attached to Mr Hoare, described as 'a man with a strong
vision, and such a determination not to be deflected off course, that he
presided over a series of actions incompatible with the handling of public
money and without regard to clear evidence that the project was going badly
wrong'.
Mr Hoare later left the authority with a Pounds 111,940 severance payment.
The committee notes that he was entitled to this under his terms of
employment, but says it is 'astonished that no disciplinary action was taken
against him'.
The report, coming soon after another from the committee on mismanagement in
West Midlands Regional Health Authority, brought opposition calls for
government action. Mr David Blunkett, shadow health secretary, called on Mrs
Virginia Bottomley, health secretary, to announce disciplinary action. Mr
John Denham, Labour MP for Southampton Itchen, called for the removal of Sir
Robin from his present position as chairman of the NHS supplies authority.
Ministers stress that management controls in the NHS have been tightened
since the Wessex and West Midlands cases came to light.
A working party is considering ways of strengthening corporate governance
and reinforcing public-service values.
Wessex Regional Health Authority Regional Information Systems Plan. HMSO.
Pounds 26.10.
</TEXT>
