<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 93 / BMA says some hospitals allow fundholder patients to jump
queues
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
More than four in 10 hospitals allow patients of GP fundholders to jump
queues for treatment, says a survey of 247 hospitals by the British Medical
Association.
In the Wessex health region, 67 per cent of hospitals admitted giving
priority to patients of fundholders, whereas less than one in five hospitals
in north-west England entered special arrangements.
Mr John Chawner, chairman of the BMA's central consultants and specialists
committee, said: 'Doctors throughout the country are committed to NHS
treatment on the basis of need - and this survey raises serious issues about
whether the present arrangements are making this top priority.'
The survey shows 42 per cent of 'fast-tracking' hospitals gave priority to
GP fundholder patients routinely as part of contract negotiations.
