<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 93 / Ford unveils credit card to rival GM
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ford has joined forces with Barclaycard to enter the UK credit card war,
following its rival Vauxhall's entry to the market in October. Ford already
issues credit cards in the US.
Ford's approach is two-pronged. It will issue Ford-Barclaycard credit cards,
available from April next year. It will also forge a link with Barclaycard's
existing customer-loyalty programme, giving Barclaycard holders the chance
of discounts on Ford cars from January.
The Ford-branded credit cards, available as Visa or Mastercard, can be seen
as a direct response to Vauxhall's GM Mastercard and Visa, to be issued from
January. Both work as normal credit cards, but heavy spenders can earn
rebates on new cars: 5 per cent of each transaction is given back as points
towards rebates of up to Pounds 600 a year (maximum Pounds 1,800) with Ford,
and Pounds 500 a year (maximum Pounds 2,500) with Vauxhall.
The difference with Ford's scheme is that it will not be necessary to have a
Ford-branded card to participate. About 3m of Barclaycard's 8m customers are
already registered with its Profiles scheme, which gives one Profiles point
for every Pounds 10 spent. Points currently buy gifts from a catalogue, but
from January they can also be used towards buying a new Ford. Cardholders
not registered with Profiles will be invited to join.
Mr Ian McAllister, chairman of Ford of Britain, predicted that the first car
bought at a discount using the Barclaycard scheme would be on the road by
the end of January. About 250,000 existing Barclaycard holders already have
enough points for a Pounds 600 rebate.
The Ford card has two disadvantages compared with the GM card. It will
charge an annual fee of Pounds 10 (waived for the first year), whereas GM
has no plans for a fee for its card. Secondly, the interest rate for
Barclaycards is higher, at 1.585 per cent a month, compared with GM's 1.53
per cent.
</TEXT>
