<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 93 / Police chiefs win power on budgets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is to give police chiefs more say over the way in which their
budgets are allocated, even before the police bill has become law.
The Home Office has told chief constables starting to prune middle-ranking
jobs that their proposals on how to spend the money saved will gain
automatic approval from next April.
Technically, police forces need permission to raise staffing levels above
their authorised quotas under rules likely to be swept away from April 1995
under the government's police reforms. The Home Office's move should in
effect remove these controls a year early.
The reduction in middle-ranking positions may lead to an increase in overall
police numbers because ministers want forces to use the money they save to
recruit more officers on the beat.
But chief constables will have discretion to use savings to buy new
equipment or invest in more crime prevention.
</TEXT>
