<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 93 / Insurers relieved over pollution damage ruling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, RICHARD LAPPER and BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Insurers of companies that cause pollution yesterday expressed relief after
a Cambridgeshire tannery won its appeal in the House of Lords against an
order to pay Pounds 1.1m in environmental damages for contaminating a water
borehole.
Had the five law lords ruled the other way, the concept of retrospective
strict liability for environmental damage would have been introduced into
English common law.
It could have left insurers facing a bill of Pounds 3bn for the cost of
cleaning up land already contaminated.
The judges ruled that Eastern Counties Leather was not liable to Cambridge
Water Company for contamination of its borehole at Sawston, Cambridgeshire,
with perchloroethene, a highly volatile solvent used by the tannery for
de-greasing animal pelts.
The judges said the tannery could not have 'reasonably foreseen' at the time
that it used the solvent, between the early 1960s and 1976, that spillages
would lead to any environmental hazard or damage at Cambridge Water's
borehole, 1.3 miles away.
The decision pleased insurers. Mr Tony Baker, head of public affairs at the
Association of British Insurers, said: 'If the appeal had not been upheld,
an element of retrospective strict liability would have been introduced.'
The Water Services Association, which represents the 10 large water and
sewerage companies of England and Wales, said: 'We are concerned about
pollution of ground water, but we are not surprised that the law lords have
ruled against retrospective liability - it is not a principle which the WSA
has sought to pursue.'
Mr Paul Taylor, a partner with Berrymans, the solicitors representing the
tannery and its insurer General Accident, said the decision meant insurers
could now assess the strength of claims against a much clearer legal
background.
'Insurers will still be absolutely concerned about environmental cover but
there are likely to be fewer claims because plaintiffs will be more
cautious,' he said.
Had the ruling gone against the tannery, insurers would have been likely to
hasten moves to narrow the scope of pollution coverage available in
commercial liability policies.
Reasonable forseeability was a prerequisite for recovery of damages under
the common law rule, the law lords said.
The rule imposes liability on a landowner who brings on to his land
something likely to cause damage if it escapes.
</TEXT>
