<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 93 / BBC audience share hopes 'wildly optimistic'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The BBC is 'wildly optimistic' in thinking it could hold on to 30 per cent
of the television audience by the end of the century, the Commons national
heritage committee warned yesterday.
Mr Gerald Kaufman, committee chairman, said the BBC would have to adapt to
the coming world of 500 channels otherwise it would 'vanish down the
technological plug'.
The BBC believes its audience share will fall to about 30 per cent by the
end of the decade from the current level of about 40 per cent.
Mr Kaufman, launching the committee's report on the future of the BBC, said
he did not see any way that the organisation's present structure could be
maintained beyond the extension of the royal charter - now being debated.
The committee predicted 'a media revolution' - with the television set
replacing 'everything from travel brochures and travel agencies to
newspapers and the postbox'.
In spite of the threat from technology, the committee decided to recommend
that the BBC's royal charter, which runs out at the end of 1996, should be
renewed for a further 10 years. They added 'with great reluctance' that the
licence-fee system of financing the BBC had 'the fewest objections to it'.
The 10-year extension, Mr Kaufman said, would give 'sufficient time for the
BBC to be able to work out a viable and vibrant future for itself'.
Future options for the BBC ranged from linking up with a large international
media conglomerate to concentrating on programme supply.
The committee also emphasised that ways must be found to make the licence
fee - at present Pounds 83 a year for colour TV - less of a burden for those
on low incomes.
Mr Kaufman appealed to the BBC to exercise humanity in prosecuting
licence-fee defaulters when it was clear they could not afford to pay.
The possibilities include: a lower-cost additional licence for households
with more than one television set, a car radio licence or one-off payment
for a car radio, large hotels paying a licence for every room beyond 50, and
dealer licences being increased from 50p to at least the level of a full
licence fee.
The National Heritage Committee also advocated that a single complaints body
should be set up to deal with every complaint relating to broadcasting.
The report was welcomed yesterday by Mr John Birt, BBC director-general, as
'a generous recognition of the BBC's value and achievements'.
National heritage committee, second report: The Future of the BBC. HMSO.
Pounds 13.25.
</TEXT>
