<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 93 / Chief executives slip back on pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Chief executives in the UK are falling further behind their international
colleagues in the pay stakes in spite of substantial salary increases in
recent months, according to a survey by Towers Perrin, the management
consultants.
However, because prices in Britain are relatively low, UK executives have
better living standards than many of their Continental colleagues.
The remuneration survey placed UK chief executives 17th in a survey of 19
countries, down from 14th the year before. US executives were top. The
survey covers industrial companies with annual sales above Pounds 165m.
When the criterion of total remuneration was used, UK chief executives fared
slightly better at 14th position. In the last survey on this measurement of
pay in 1991 UK executives ranked sixth.
Towers Perrin said a number of factors were influencing this change. They
included:
Exchange rate movements.
The adoption by other countries of annual bonus schemes and other forms of
longer term incentives.
Shortage of management talent in other countries which was driving up pay
rates.
In terms of purchasing power, chief executives in the UK had 63 per cent of
the purchasing power of US chief executives. German chief executives had 65
per cent, Italy 64 per cent, Spain 62 per cent, Switzerland 61 per cent,
France 55 per cent, Netherlands 54 per cent, Belgium 44 per cent and Sweden
31 per cent.
Worldwide Total Remuneration Survey. Marketing Department, Towers Perrin,
77-91 New Oxford Street, London WC1A 1PX. Free.
</TEXT>
