<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 93 / Corporate Names to get more power
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lloyd's of London yesterday introduced new voting rules, significantly
increasing the power of new corporate members in the insurance market.
More than 16 new corporate Names - investment trusts and companies and
insurance companies - are injecting some Pounds 850m into the market and
will provide backing of about Pounds 1.5bn in 1994, just under a fifth of
the total.
The rules allocate votes proportionate to allocated capacity (the amount of
premiums syndicates are permitted to underwrite).
Individual Names, whose assets have traditionally supported the market, will
have voting rights proportionate to their allocated capacity - but this has
been divided on a 'one-member-one-vote' basis.
The new voting arrangements are transitional. It is envisaged that voting at
general meetings will ultimately be weighted in proportion to capacity.
Lloyd's also announced new mandatory qualifications for active underwriters
and underwriting agency directors.
Active underwriters appointed after December 31 next year must be associates
of the Chartered Insurance Institute - instead of the current requirement
that they obtain a Lloyd's Market Certificate.
</TEXT>
