FT  10 DEC 93 / Offers invited for four pits
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
British Coal is inviting private-sector companies to operate four of the
eight pits where it has recently ceased production and is considering
arrangements for the others. Potential licensees have been asked to register
interest in Calverton and Rufford, Nottinghamshire; Bentley, Yorkshire; and
Wearmouth, Tyne and Wear.
The corporation is considering tenders to resume mining at six pits: Betws,
south Wales; Rossington and Markham Main, Yorkshire; Clipstone,
Nottinghamshire; Trentham, Staffordshire; and Coventry, west Midlands.
It will today announce that 180 jobs are to go at Ellington colliery,
Northumberland - north-east England's last pit.
A government decision rejecting plans for an open-cast coal mine near
Hadrian's Wall was upheld in the High Court. Coal Contractors, based in
Chesterfield, Derbyshire, wanted to mine on a site near Corbridge,
Northumberland.
