<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 93 / Jobs in councils fall by 50,000
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Local government employment in England and Wales fell by 50,000 in the year
to September 1993. This allowed a static pay bill in spite of an increase in
pay over that period of more than 3 per cent, the Local Government
Management Board said yesterday.
Mr Jack Straw, the shadow environment secretary, said the government had
broken its assurances that council-tax capping would not lead to job cuts.
The government will argue that the figures show it is possible to keep the
pay bill flat, as required until 1997, and still award wage rises.
The total number of jobs in local government in England and Wales is
slightly below 2m.
The 50,000 fall excludes the effects of the transfer of further and higher
education out of the local authority sector, cuts due to compulsory
competitive tendering, and changes associated with schools moving to
grant-maintained status.
About 11,700 of the total is due to redundancy and the rest derived from
natural wastage.
The 50,000 fall included 20,800 full-time non-manual workers, 12,700
full-time manuals and 27,700 part-time manuals. Part-time non-manuals
increased over the period by 11,700.
</TEXT>
