<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 93 / Iraq frees Britons after Saddam sees Heath in Baghdad
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Former British prime minister Sir Edward Heath yesterday secured the release
of three British prisoners held in Iraq, write James Whittington in Amman
and Agencies. The men were freed after Sir Edward met President Saddam
Hussein in Baghdad.
Mr Michael Wainwright, 42, and Mr Paul Ride, 33, were jailed last year for
10 and seven years respectively on charges of entering Iraq illegally. Mr
Simon Dunn, 23, was arrested in June and sentenced to eight years for the
same offence.
They were due to fly with Sir Edward by helicopter today to the Jordanian
capital, Amman, where they will be reunited with their families before
travelling on to the UK.
Iraq previously linked their release with Britain's unfreezing of Iraqi
assets in the UK. But British diplomats in Amman stressed that 'no deal had
been done'. One said the move was a gesture by Saddam in the hope UN
sanctions would soon be lifted.
</TEXT>
