<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 93 / S African oil embargo to end
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The United Nations yesterday agreed to the unrestricted resumption of
shipments of oil and petroleum products to South Africa, ending a 16-year
embargo that was widely observed although not mandatory, writes Michael
Littlejohns in New York.
Mr Samuel Insanally, president of the UN General Assembly, announced the
decision in comformity with an October 8 resolution that proposed the
lifting of sanctions when the South African Transitional Executive Council
became operational. The only measure now remaining against South Africa is a
mandatory arms embargo imposed by the Security Council in 1977 which is
expected to continue until after elections in April.
</TEXT>
