<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 93 / Poll shows election strength of Russian neo-fascists
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Russia's neo-fascist party could become the second-largest faction in the
parliament which Russia will elect on Sunday, according to a survey by one
of Russia's more authoritative pollsters.
A poll by the All-Russian Centre for Public Opinion Research, which cannot
be published inside Russia in the week before elections, gave Mr Vladimir
Zhirinovsky's Liberal Democratic party 14 per cent support among voters who
have decided how they will vote.
Mr Zhirinovsky's party is anything but liberal-democratic, promising to
conquer Russia's neighbours, including Turkey, to gain access to warm-water
ports. Domestically, he is offering Russians who feel impoverished and
humiliated an alternative to the Communists of the discredited past and to
the various democratic parties which are promising ambitious market reforms
with varying degrees of pain.
The poll puts the extreme nationalist leader behind Russia's Choice, headed
by deputy prime minister Yegor Gaidar, with 22.3 per cent support.
It coincided with warnings of 'a new round of struggle and new conflicts'
from President Boris Yeltsin if Russians failed to support the constitution,
which would give him sweeping powers, in a referendum, also on Sunday.
However, Mr Sergei Yuzhenkov, deputy head of the federal information centre
and an organiser of Russia's Choice, said even if Mr Zhirinovsky did well,
Mr Yeltsin would be free to choose whatever government he pleased.
He added that if the constitution - which empowers the president to dissolve
parliament if it turns down his candidate for prime minister - was rejected,
Mr Yeltsin would continue to rule by decree until the new basic law was
pushed through parliament.
Although Russian polls tend to be less reliable than those in the west, this
survey indicates the effectiveness of Mr Zhirinovsky's homespun campaign in
exploiting the weariness of Russian voters with their present rulers.
Mr Gaidar said this week he feared the new State Duma would be as difficult
as the old Supreme Soviet dissolved by Mr Yeltsin. Yesterday, he said such
results would confirm his warnings of the dangers of the divisions among
Russian democrats who put personal ambition ahead of the country's
interests.
The poll puts Mr Grigory Yavlinsky's reformist Yabloko bloc in third place
with 13.6 per cent, followed by the conservative Democratic Party of Russia
and the Communists with 7.8 per cent and 7.7 per cent respectively.
Together, all democrats who favour similar market reforms would barely
scrape together half of the seats in a new parliament, according to the
poll.
Apart from Mr Yavlinsky, the two other parties which would constitute
natural allies for Russia's Choice are the Russian Party of Unity and
Accord, headed by deputy Prime Minister Sergei Shakhrai, and the Democratic
Reform Movement headed by the St Petersburg mayor Mr Anatoly Sobchak.
Russian nightmares, Page 3
</TEXT>
