<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 93 / EU reacts angrily to shipping offer in trade talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL and FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Hopes of liberalising international trade in services in the Uruguay Round
talks were thrown into disarray yesterday when negotiators reacted angrily
to details of the US offer on shipping.
Other important services sectors such as banking and securities have been
the subject of controversy for several weeks, and the US and European Union
remain at loggerheads over access to Europe's film and television market. If
shipping drops off the negotiating table, Geneva officials acknowledged the
services deal would be in tatters.
EU trade negotiators aroused consternation yesterday by saying they would
finalise tariff-cutting deals with just 15 to 20 countries before the
Uruguay Round deadline next Wednesday.
Mr Peter Sutherland, director-general of the General Agreement on Tariffs
and Trade, insisted the EU 'must find the time, and the personnel, to bring
the Round to a conclusion' on time.
The EU thought it had won an important concession from Washington on ocean
shipping in talks on Monday in Brussels between Mr Mickey Kantor, US trade
representative, and Sir Leon Brittan, his EU counterpart. But angry EU
negotiators discovered yesterday the offer amounted to less than they had
believed.
One US official claimed there had been an 'unintentional misunderstanding'.
The US has agreed only to include cargo reservation systems in the services
package, about 3 per cent of the ocean shipping sector. Even here, the offer
is only a commitment not to tighten restrictions, which reserve 75 per cent
of the business for US flagged ships.
'It looks like maritime is going to be out of the Round,' said one gloomy EU
negotiator. 'The US position is killing negotiations in this sector.'
Liberalisation of shipping services is a key demand for EU members, Denmark
and Greece, as well as the Nordic countries.
The EU says it will withdraw its own offer on maritime services, which is
conditional on a 'critical mass' of other countries also liberalising their
shipping sectors, if Washington does not put a better deal on the table.
Trade officials fear that if one key services sector is 'carved out' of the
Uruguay Round liberalisation package, others will follow.
The EU has served notice that, despite partial agreement with the US in
Brussels on Monday, it may not be able to resist French pressure to keep the
sensitive audio-visual sector out of the Round.
One trade official said: 'If the US and the EU really do fall out over
maritime and audio-visual services, then this is a very dangerous
development indeed. The two need to get back around a table and cobble this
together.'
Trade diplomats are also critical of Washington's stand on financial
services, where the US aims to grant unrestricted access to its banking and
securities market only to countries providing full access to the US
financial services industry.
Summit faces discord, Page 2
Two-stage Gatt deal, Page 6
Editorial Comment, Page 17
Attack by Clarke, Page 18
</TEXT>
